column1: OMAP-37: Organ Mapping Antibody Panel (OMAP) for Multiplexed Antibody-Based Imaging of Human Liver with MICS

column2: Christoph Herbel; Salpy Baghdo; Julia Femel

column24: rationale
CD34 is a well-established marker of vascular endothelial cells and is used to label hepatic blood endothelial cells, facilitating the identification of vascular compartments within liver tissue.
CD45 is a pan-leukocyte marker that broadly labels all hematopoietic cells. It is instrumental in assessing immune cell infiltration and overall immune landscape within hepatic microenvironments.

CD5 is expressed on all T cells and a subset of B cells. It plays a regulatory role in T-cell receptor (TCR) and B-cell receptor (BCR) signaling, making it valuable for profiling lymphocyte subsets and their activation states
CD68 is a lysosomal glycoprotein expressed by myeloid cells, including Kupffer cells and dendritic cells. It is commonly used to identify phagocytic cells and assess innate immune responses.
GFAP marks hepatic stellate cells located in the perisinusoidal space. It is a key marker for identifying mesenchymal activation and fibrogenic potential in liver tissue.
KRT19 is an intermediate filament protein expressed in epithelial cells of the bile ducts and ductules. It is essential for delineating the biliary tree and epithelial integrity.
CD146 (MCAM) is expressed on endothelial cells of the hepatic vasculature, pericytes, and hematopoietic stem cells. It supports vascular and stromal compartmentalization.
CD326 (EpCAM) is a transmembrane glycoprotein expressed on hepatic stem/progenitor cells and bile duct epithelial cells. It is used to identify regenerative niches and epithelial lineage commitment.
CD105 (Endoglin) is a marker of endothelial cells, particularly within hepatic sinusoids. It is involved in angiogenesis and vascular remodeling.
CD140b (PDGFRbeta) is expressed on mesenchymal cells and pericytes, contributing to stromal architecture and perivascular signaling.
CD31 (PECAM-1) labels endothelial cells lining blood vessels and is critical for mapping vascular networks and endothelial junctions.
CD4 is a canonical marker of T helper cells, enabling the identification of adaptive immune subsets and their spatial distribution.
KRT7 stains stratified cuboidal epithelial cells of the biliary ducts, aiding in the structural delineation of ductal systems.
CD10 marks bile canaliculi and biliary epithelium, useful for profiling hepatobiliary interfaces and epithelial polarity.
KLF2 is a transcription factor involved in flow sensing and homeostasis of cholangiocytes. It plays a role in maintaining functional integrity of the biliary epithelium.
Vimentin is a cytoskeletal protein expressed in hepatic stellate cells and faintly in bile duct epithelial cells. It is indicative of mesenchymal activation and epithelial-mesenchymal transitions.
Arginase 1 is a hepatocyte-specific enzyme involved in nitrogen metabolism. It serves as a robust marker for hepatocyte identification
CD45RA is expressed on naïve/resting T cells, B cells, NK cells, medullary thymocytes, and plasmacytoid dendritic cells. It aids in distinguishing immune cell maturation states.
CD90 (THY-1) stains hepatic portal fibroblasts and hepatic stellate cells, contributing to stromal and fibrotic profiling
CD74 functions as a receptor for macrophage migration inhibitory factor (MIF), relevant for inflammatory signaling and antigen presentation
CD163 is expressed on Kupffer cells and M2-polarized macrophages, serving as a marker for anti-inflammatory and tissue-resident macrophage populations
Glutamine Synthetase (GS) is expressed in pericentral hepatocytes near central veins. It plays a key role in nitrogen metabolism and is a marker for metabolic zonation.
CD169 (Siglec-1) is expressed on Kupffer cells and defines a subset of macrophages situated between liver sinusoids, involved in antigen capture and immune surveillance.
CD64 (FcγRI) is a high-affinity Fc receptor expressed on macrophages, particularly those with systemic distribution, useful for identifying activated myeloid cells.
CD11c (ITGAX) is expressed on dendritic cells and macrophages located near the liver capsule, supporting spatial mapping of antigen-presenting cells.
CD45RO marks memory and activated T cells, as well as subsets of granulocytes, monocytes, and B cells, enabling functional immune profiling
CD49a (ITGA1) is an integrin expressed on tissue-resident memory T cells. It pairs with integrin β1 and binds to collagen IV, anchoring cells within the hepatic matrix.
CD16 (FcγRIII) is expressed on monocytes, macrophages, platelets, and neutrophils, facilitating the identification of cytotoxic and phagocytic immune subsets
CD3e is a component of the TCR-CD3 complex and serves as a universal marker for T cells, essential for adaptive immune profiling
CD11b (ITGAM) is a myeloid marker and NK cell antigen, used to identify innate immune populations and inflammatory responses
CD56 (NCAM1) CD56 is expressed on liver-specific NK cells, supporting the characterization of innate lymphoid compartments.
CAIX (Carbonic Anhydrase IX) is a hypoxia-regulated transmembrane protein expressed on cholangiocytes, useful for assessing oxygen gradients and ductal stress.
CD20 is a canonical B cell marker, enabling the identification of humoral immune components.
Podoplanin stains lymphatic endothelial cells and occasionally bile duct epithelial cells, contributing to lymphatic and ductal mapping.
Hep-Par1 recognizes mitochondrial antigens in hepatocytes, serving as a reliable marker for parenchymal cell identification.
CD45RB is a splice variant of CD45 and is used to assess activation states of B and T cells, supporting functional immune profiling.
Ki-67 is a nuclear antigen expressed in proliferating cells, used to quantify cellular turnover and regenerative activity.
Alpha-Smooth Muscle Actin (α-SMA) stains sinusoidal endothelial cells, vascular smooth muscle cells, and activated fibroblasts, relevant for vascular integrity and fibrotic remodeling.
This marker stains connective tissue, supporting assessment of extracellular matrix deposition and fibrosis.
Similar to type III, collagen type IV α1 chain marks basement membrane components and connective tissue, aiding in structural tissue analysis.
